{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":92420,"duration_api_ms":119285,"num_turns":5,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"129fd1e0-b7c2-4a01-adc6-b5c7f525b9c8","total_cost_usd":0.3681901000000001,"usage":{"input_tokens":2020,"cache_creation_input_tokens":26603,"cache_read_input_tokens":76409,"output_tokens":3585,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":26603,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":55,"outputTokens":4890,"cacheReadInputTokens":155481,"cacheCreationInputTokens":19151,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.06399185,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":2020,"outputTokens":3585,"cacheReadInputTokens":76409,"cacheCreationInputTokens":26603,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.30419825,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"All six amendments identify genuine issues in the codebase. Three relate to the incomplete/inconsistent FailureClass classification pipeline (fr-6-2cb763cc, fr-6-e8329596, fr-6-20911add), one identifies a timeout contract regression (fr-6-fe06dd51), one flags a code hygiene issue with an unused parameter (fr-6-ba44d45e), and one identifies a fragile numeric conversion pattern (fr-6-332f0f81). Each amendment is well-supported by the actual code.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-6-2cb763cc","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at process_backend.rs:1192-1201: a missing OPENROUTER_API_KEY is classified as FailureClass::BinaryNotFound. This is semantically wrong — the FailureClass enum has no ConfigurationError variant, so BinaryNotFound was repurposed as a general 'fatal infrastructure' signal. Operator diagnostics and logs will report 'binary_not_found' for a missing env var, which is actively misleading. Either a new variant should be added or the existing classification should be clearly documented as a known overload."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-ba44d45e","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at process_backend.rs:1452-1461: classify_exit_failure takes _status: ExitStatus (prefixed with underscore, confirming it's unused) and unconditionally returns TransportFailure. The detailed doc comment explains the design rationale well, but an unused parameter in a function that was clearly designed to be filled in later is a code hygiene issue. The amendment's suggestion to either remove the parameter (if the design is truly final) or document it as a deliberate no-op is reasonable and low-risk."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-332f0f81","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at retry_policy.rs:110: the function computes 2u64.saturating_pow(attempt.saturating_sub(1)) then does multiplier.try_into().unwrap_or(u32::MAX) to convert u64 back to u32 for Duration::saturating_mul. For attempt >= 33, 2^32 overflows u32 and silently falls back to u32::MAX. While backoff_cap saves the final result, the intermediate u64→u32 lossy conversion via try_into().unwrap_or(u32::MAX) is fragile and unnecessary. Using 2u32.saturating_pow(...) directly is simpler, avoids the type mismatch, and produces identical semantics (saturates at u32::MAX for large exponents)."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-fe06dd51","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at service.rs:202: the service-level timeout is now request.timeout + 30s, with a comment saying the adapter enforces its own hard timeout. But the stub backend (used in tests) does NOT enforce its own timeout — it only sleeps cooperatively. The test at agent_execution_test.rs:292-316 creates a 10ms timeout request with a 100ms-sleeping stub, expecting InvocationTimeout. With the +30s buffer, the service timeout is ~30.01s, so the 100ms stub completes well before the safety net fires. This is a real regression: the timeout contract is broken for any adapter that relies on the service-level guard rather than implementing its own hard deadline."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-e8329596","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at process_backend.rs:1452-1461: classify_exit_failure ignores ExitStatus and returns TransportFailure for all exit codes including 127. The test at process_backend_test.rs:2038-2068 codifies this by asserting exit 127 produces TransportFailure. While the code's comment offers a reasonable rationale (post-spawn exit codes are application-defined), this contradicts the stated acceptance criterion that exit 127 should fail immediately without consuming retry budget. A shell returning 127 because the target command doesn't exist is functionally a missing-binary scenario even though the shell process itself spawned successfully. The implementation should at minimum differentiate this case or explicitly document the deviation from the acceptance criteria."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-20911add","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified at engine.rs:5954-5962 and 6430-6446: availability check errors from check_availability() are rewrapped into AppError::BackendUnavailable with failure_class: None. Per error.rs:311, failure_class() defaults None to TransportFailure for BackendUnavailable variants. This means if check_availability returns a BinaryNotFound error (e.g., the backend binary doesn't exist), the classification is silently downgraded to TransportFailure, making it retryable. This defeats the purpose of the BinaryNotFound classification for required availability checks on refiners, planners, and arbiters. The fix is to propagate the original failure_class from the check_availability error rather than hardcoding None."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"aab0e9ac-968e-4f1a-b0df-05b6275ab1a8"}
